{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"I’m going around the world giving talks about Darwin,"},{"time":3000,"text":"and usually what I’m talking about"},{"time":5000,"text":"is Darwin’s strange inversion of reasoning."},{"time":8000,"text":"Now that title, that phrase, comes from a critic, an early critic,"},{"time":13000,"text":"and this is a passage that I just love, and would like to read for you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":17000,"text":"\"In the theory with which we have to deal, Absolute Ignorance is the artificer;"},{"time":22000,"text":"so that we may enunciate as the fundamental principle of the whole system,"},{"time":27000,"text":"that, in order to make a perfect and beautiful machine,"},{"time":30000,"text":"it is not requisite to know how to make it."},{"time":33000,"text":"This proposition will be found on careful examination to express,"},{"time":37000,"text":"in condensed form, the essential purport of the Theory,"},{"time":41000,"text":"and to express in a few words all Mr. Darwin’s meaning;"},{"time":45000,"text":"who, by a strange inversion of reasoning,"},{"time":49000,"text":"seems to think Absolute Ignorance fully qualified"},{"time":52000,"text":"to take the place of Absolute Wisdom in the achievements of creative skill.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":58000,"text":"Exactly. Exactly. And it is a strange inversion."},{"time":65000,"text":"A creationist pamphlet has this wonderful page in it:"},{"time":69000,"text":"\"Test Two:"},{"time":71000,"text":"Do you know of any building that didn’t have a builder? Yes/No."},{"time":75000,"text":"Do you know of any painting that didn’t have a painter? Yes/No."},{"time":78000,"text":"Do you know of any car that didn’t have a maker? Yes/No."},{"time":82000,"text":"If you answered 'Yes' for any of the above, give details.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":87000,"text":"A-ha! I mean, it really is a strange inversion of reasoning."},{"time":93000,"text":"You would have thought it stands to reason"},{"time":97000,"text":"that design requires an intelligent designer."},{"time":101000,"text":"But Darwin shows that it’s just false."}]},{"cues":[{"time":103000,"text":"Today, though, I’m going to talk about Darwin’s other strange inversion,"},{"time":108000,"text":"which is equally puzzling at first, but in some ways just as important."},{"time":114000,"text":"It stands to reason that we love chocolate cake because it is sweet."},{"time":121000,"text":"Guys go for girls like this because they are sexy."},{"time":127000,"text":"We adore babies because they’re so cute."},{"time":131000,"text":"And, of course, we are amused by jokes because they are funny."}]},{"cues":[{"time":140000,"text":"This is all backwards. It is. And Darwin shows us why."},{"time":147000,"text":"Let’s start with sweet. Our sweet tooth is basically an evolved sugar detector,"},{"time":155000,"text":"because sugar is high energy, and it’s just been wired up to the preferer,"},{"time":159000,"text":"to put it very crudely, and that’s why we like sugar."},{"time":164000,"text":"Honey is sweet because we like it, not \"we like it because honey is sweet.\""},{"time":171000,"text":"There’s nothing intrinsically sweet about honey."},{"time":176000,"text":"If you looked at glucose molecules till you were blind,"},{"time":180000,"text":"you wouldn’t see why they tasted sweet."},{"time":183000,"text":"You have to look in our brains to understand why they’re sweet."},{"time":189000,"text":"So if you think first there was sweetness,"},{"time":191000,"text":"and then we evolved to like sweetness,"},{"time":193000,"text":"you’ve got it backwards; that’s just wrong. It’s the other way round."},{"time":197000,"text":"Sweetness was born with the wiring which evolved."}]},{"cues":[{"time":201000,"text":"And there’s nothing intrinsically sexy about these young ladies."},{"time":205000,"text":"And it’s a good thing that there isn’t, because if there were,"},{"time":210000,"text":"then Mother Nature would have a problem:"},{"time":214000,"text":"How on earth do you get chimps to mate?"},{"time":221000,"text":"Now you might think, ah, there’s a solution: hallucinations."},{"time":229000,"text":"That would be one way of doing it, but there’s a quicker way."},{"time":233000,"text":"Just wire the chimps up to love that look,"},{"time":236000,"text":"and apparently they do."},{"time":239000,"text":"That’s all there is to it."},{"time":244000,"text":"Over six million years, we and the chimps evolved our different ways."},{"time":248000,"text":"We became bald-bodied, oddly enough;"},{"time":251000,"text":"for one reason or another, they didn’t."},{"time":255000,"text":"If we hadn’t, then probably this would be the height of sexiness."}]},{"cues":[{"time":267000,"text":"Our sweet tooth is an evolved and instinctual preference for high-energy food."},{"time":272000,"text":"It wasn’t designed for chocolate cake."},{"time":275000,"text":"Chocolate cake is a supernormal stimulus."},{"time":278000,"text":"The term is owed to Niko Tinbergen,"},{"time":280000,"text":"who did his famous experiments with gulls,"},{"time":282000,"text":"where he found that that orange spot on the gull’s beak --"},{"time":286000,"text":"if he made a bigger, oranger spot"},{"time":288000,"text":"the gull chicks would peck at it even harder."},{"time":290000,"text":"It was a hyperstimulus for them, and they loved it."},{"time":293000,"text":"What we see with, say, chocolate cake"},{"time":297000,"text":"is it’s a supernormal stimulus to tweak our design wiring."},{"time":302000,"text":"And there are lots of supernormal stimuli; chocolate cake is one."},{"time":305000,"text":"There's lots of supernormal stimuli for sexiness."}]},{"cues":[{"time":308000,"text":"And there's even supernormal stimuli for cuteness. Here’s a pretty good example."},{"time":314000,"text":"It’s important that we love babies, and that we not be put off by, say, messy diapers."},{"time":319000,"text":"So babies have to attract our affection and our nurturing, and they do."},{"time":325000,"text":"And, by the way, a recent study shows that mothers"},{"time":329000,"text":"prefer the smell of the dirty diapers of their own baby."},{"time":332000,"text":"So nature works on many levels here."},{"time":335000,"text":"But now, if babies didn’t look the way they do -- if babies looked like this,"},{"time":340000,"text":"that’s what we would find adorable, that’s what we would find --"},{"time":344000,"text":"we would think, oh my goodness, do I ever want to hug that."},{"time":350000,"text":"This is the strange inversion."}]},{"cues":[{"time":352000,"text":"Well now, finally what about funny. My answer is, it’s the same story, the same story."},{"time":359000,"text":"This is the hard one, the one that isn’t obvious. That’s why I leave it to the end."},{"time":363000,"text":"And I won’t be able to say too much about it."},{"time":365000,"text":"But you have to think evolutionarily, you have to think, what hard job that has to be done --"},{"time":371000,"text":"it’s dirty work, somebody’s got to do it --"},{"time":374000,"text":"is so important to give us such a powerful, inbuilt reward for it when we succeed."},{"time":382000,"text":"Now, I think we've found the answer -- I and a few of my colleagues."},{"time":386000,"text":"It’s a neural system that’s wired up to reward the brain"},{"time":390000,"text":"for doing a grubby clerical job."},{"time":396000,"text":"Our bumper sticker for this view is"},{"time":400000,"text":"that this is the joy of debugging."},{"time":403000,"text":"Now I’m not going to have time to spell it all out,"},{"time":405000,"text":"but I’ll just say that only some kinds of debugging get the reward."},{"time":410000,"text":"And what we’re doing is we’re using humor as a sort of neuroscientific probe"},{"time":418000,"text":"by switching humor on and off, by turning the knob on a joke --"},{"time":422000,"text":"now it’s not funny ... oh, now it’s funnier ..."},{"time":424000,"text":"now we’ll turn a little bit more ... now it’s not funny --"},{"time":426000,"text":"in this way, we can actually learn something"},{"time":429000,"text":"about the architecture of the brain,"},{"time":431000,"text":"the functional architecture of the brain."}]},{"cues":[{"time":433000,"text":"Matthew Hurley is the first author of this. We call it the Hurley Model."},{"time":438000,"text":"He’s a computer scientist, Reginald Adams a psychologist, and there I am,"},{"time":442000,"text":"and we’re putting this together into a book."},{"time":444000,"text":"Thank you very much."}]}]}